* updateLocation() computes the location field from the location fields of the heirs (descendants).  This would seem to be a matter of just copying the location fields of the first and last heirs, in the  obvious way.  However, there seem to be some nodes with no heirs that have their locations set to (java.lang.Integer.MAX_VALUE, ...MAX_VALUE, ...MIN_VALUE, ...MIN_VALUE) The only ones I've found are N_IdPrefix nodes, which don't have any corresponding tokens in the module.  Instead of being efficient and looking for the first and last heirs that have a real location, we write a simple loop that works regardless of how the heirs are ordered.   LL 26 Nov 2009

* Create a list of overrides. If the override is not in the spec's root module, then the config file will have     A <- [M] id . This means that A is defined in module M, and its definition is being overriden in the spec root module which is dependent upon M. The following is an example from Leslie Lamport that explains the code. Let's suppose we have ------ MODULE MA ---- IB == INSTANCE MB ... ================= ------ MODULE MB ---- IC == INSTANCE MC ... ================= ----- MODULE MC ------ Foo == ... ====================== where MA is the spec's root module.  The user will see in the override menu and override IB!IC!Foo Let OD be the OpDefNode for IB!IC!Foo in the semantic tree for module MA.  Then OD.getSource() is the OpDefNode for Foo in the semantic tree of module MC.  So we have OD.getSource().getOriginallyDefinedInModuleNode()  is the module node for MC, and OD.getSource().getOriginallyDefinedInModuleNode().getName().toString() = ""MC"" OD.getName().toString() = ""Foo"" and the config file should contain Foo <-[MC] ...

* First try to get the information from parser's printed output.
Here's what I've found out about messages when there's a parsing error. The message with the error looks like one of the following:
- ""Lexical error at line n, column n."" + message

- ""***Parse Error***"" + Message + ""at line n, column n""
+ Message

- ""Parse Error Precedence conflict between
ops /\ in block line n, col m to line m, col
of module Foo and / "" + message

The preceding message is

""Parsing module Naturals in file
C:\users\lamport ...\Naturals.tla""

which is produced by a call to ToolIO.out.println in
ParseUnit.parseFile

When such a message is produced, the parseErrors just contains
a single abort that is useless. However, the preceding kind of
error message isn't produced for the following kinds of errors:

1. A module's file can't be read.
2. There's a circular EXTENDS/INSTANCES dependency.
3. The module name is different from the file name.

The abort is ""Unknown location "" + message, where message
is:

1. ""Cannot find source file for module Foo""
2. ""Circular dependency among .tla files
column2:
dependency cycle...""
3. ""File name 'Foo' does not match the name 'Foobar"""" of the
top level module it contains.""
In the first two errors, the last ""Parsing module"" message does not contain the name of the module with the error, and there seems to be no way to figure out in what module the error is.
The first type of message also includes the following rare variants.

- ""Error: Failed to open output file Foo\n ..."" which occurs if there's an IOException.
- ""Error: source file 'Foo' has apparently been deleted."" which occurs I have no idea when
There's also
- ""Could not parse module Foo from file FooBar""
I have no idea when that is produced.
